How to Finance the Green Transition
New York—This week, world leaders gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global battle against climate change and submit new emissions reduction commitments.
The climate crisis is of utmost importance, and our pace of action is far too slow.
We are slow to shift into high gear.
Accelerating the pace of change requires collaborative efforts from both public and private sectors.
Fortunately, through the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector collaboration to combat climate change is increasingly growing.
Under the leadership of Michael Bloomberg, the UN Climate Action Special Envoy, CFLI was established with the mission of mobilizing private capital at the global level to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report titled "Financing the Low Carbon Future," outlining how to expand green finance to support an orderly transition to a low-carbon economy and presenting public-private partnership opportunities to achieve the goals of the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the world's largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects.
But now, in response to the call by European heads of state and the newly elected President of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, we are ready to demonstrate greater ambition and strengthen the role of EIB as the EU's dedicated climate bank.
EIB will mainstream climate considerations, target low-carbon investments specifically, and commit at least 1 trillion euros to low-carbon projects over the next decade.
To achieve this goal, at least 50% of EIB financing will be allocated to climate action and environmental sustainability by 2025.
By the end of 2020, we will align all of our financing activities with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects dependent on fossil fuels.
Furthermore, we will position EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to help economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As an EU bank, our mission is to invest in Europe's future, and among the most important issues is climate change.
How urgent the climate crisis is, that strong our resolve is.
It was during this summer that European countries experienced record-breaking high temperatures and poor crop yields, due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-related phenomena cost major cities billions of dollars each year, and threaten even more lives.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, as funding new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues cities around the world.
Shifting the investment model will accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels. This transition has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy and moving away from fossil fuels.
By 2011, nearly half of America's coal-fired power plants had retired, while its clean energy sector created 3.3 million jobs, compared to fewer than 100,000 in the coal industry.
Moreover, an increasing number of American cities and states have committed to achieving net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from the Beyond Carbon initiative, launched by the Bloomberg Philanthropies last year, which aims to support the complete decarbonization of the U.S. economy.
As the international community, we must not only invest in clean energy but also reduce investments in dirty energy.
Currently, from the perspective of fossil fuel subsidies, we are essentially spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investments toward electric vehicles and other technologies that can drive transformative changes toward a green transition.
These investments will yield substantial returns, including reducing the huge costs that air pollution imposes on public health.
In addition, we can take numerous measures to steer the necessary funding.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, businesses and investors have been unaware of climate-related risks, not knowing the rationale behind reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from the impacts of extreme weather.
This is beginning to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding businesses to allocate capital in a more sustainable manner and enabling investors to reward companies that seriously address climate change.
Second, we must clarify investment risks related to green finance.
Cities account for more than 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a few cities in the developing world are able to obtain credit ratings.
As a result, total investments in clean public transportation, energy-efficient buildings, and other emission-reduction projects have been affected.
Governments and listed banks must step up their efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including through initiatives such as the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led by Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Third, we need to modernize the power grid.
Incentives such as refunds and tax breaks have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for both businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar programs to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies, speeding up the overcoming of intermittency issues.
Moreover, better grid connectivity can allow regions with surplus wind and solar power to supply electricity to regions experiencing shortages.
Governments can play a leading role in these two areas, encouraging more private investment to flow into clean energy.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has expanded to $136 billion.
But compared to the global bond market worth $10 trillion, it is but a drop in the bucket.
Therefore, the EIB is helping the EU develop a classification system for sustainable finance standards, so that investors can compare similar projects, just as with standard bonds.
More and better information about the carbon footprint of investments can enable investors to make informed decisions, thereby directing more private investment toward low-carbon projects.
This is how we provide financing for the green transition.
